The article discusses the Homestar Energy Efficiency Retrofit Program, which was proposed by President Obama to incentivize homeowners to make energy-efficient improvements to their homes. The program aims to create jobs, boost demand for energy efficiency products and services, and reduce dependence on oil. The key components of the program include direct rebates for consumers, with up to $1,000 - $1,500 for simple upgrades and $3,000 for comprehensive energy retrofits. The program also requires certified contractors and oversight to ensure quality installations. Additionally, the program supports financing options for consumers and is expected to result in the creation of tens of thousands of jobs and substantial energy savings. The article also mentions some business leaders and local efficiency contractors who support the program.